Creating a dynamic keyboard with glowing key effects upon physical keyboard press and a word-triggered webpage navigation feature involves a significant amount of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript coding. Below is a basic example that includes a virtual keyboard, an output section, and a JavaScript section where you can add specific words and their corresponding webpages. The script includes event listeners for both the virtual and physical keyboard inputs.

Please note that, for security reasons, changing the location of the page (to load another webpage) through the input of words is not typically recommended as it can lead to security vulnerabilities or unexpected behavior. Adjustments need to be made according to your security policies. Make sure to test thoroughly and ensure proper validation and sanitation of input if implementing on a live site.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Virtual Keyboard</title>
<style>
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}
.keyboard-container {
    text-align: center;
}
.key {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 5px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 5px;
    cursor: pointer;
    user-select: none;
    transition: background-color 0.3s, box-shadow 0.3s;
}
.key:hover, .key:active,
.key.glow {
    background-color: #eaeaea;
    box-shadow: 0 0 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
}
.output {
    width: 100%;
    height: 150px;
    margin-top: 20px;
    padding: 10px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 5px;
    font-size: 18px;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="keyboard-container">
    <div id="keyboard"></div>
</div>

<textarea id="output" class="output" placeholder="Type here or use the virtual keyboard..."></textarea>

<script>
const keys = [
    '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7', '8', '9', '0',
    'q', 'w', 'e', 'r', 't', 'y', 'u', 'i', 'o', 'p',
    'a', 's', 'd', 'f', 'g', 'h', 'j', 'k', 'l',
    'z', 'x', 'c', 'v', 'b', 'n', 'm',
    'Space', 'Enter', 'Backspace'
];

const wordToURL = {
    // Add your list of words and their corresponding webpages here
    // Example: 'google': 'https://www.google.com'
};

const keyboardElement = document.getElementById('keyboard');
const outputElement = document.getElementById('output');

// Create virtual keyboard
keys.forEach(key => {
    const keyElement = document.createElement('div');
    keyElement.textContent = key.length === 1 ? key.toUpperCase() : key;
    keyElement.className = 'key';
    keyElement.setAttribute('data-key', key.toUpperCase());
    keyboardElement.appendChild(keyElement);

    // Virtual key event
    keyElement.addEventListener('click', () => {
        handleKeyInput(key);
    });
});

// Physical keyboard press event
window.addEventListener('keydown', e => {
    const keyElement = document.querySelector(`.key[data-key="${e.key.toUpperCase()}"]`);
    if (keyElement) {
        handleKeyInput(e.key);
        keyElement.classList.add('glow');
    }
});

// Remove glow effect on key release
window.addEventListener('keyup', e => {
    const keyElement = document.querySelector(`.key[data-key="${e.key.toUpperCase()}"]`);
    if (keyElement) {
        keyElement.classList.remove('glow');
    }
});

function handleKeyInput(key) {
    let value = outputElement.value;
    switch (key) {
        case 'Space':
            value += ' ';
            break;
        case 'Enter':
            // find if current input matches any of the words in the wordToURL mapping
            navigateToPage(value.trim());
            value += '\n';
            break;
        case 'Backspace':
            value = value.substring(0, value.length - 1);
            break;
        default:
            if (key.length === 1) value += key; // add character key
    }
    outputElement.value = value;
}

function navigateToPage(input) {
    if (wordToURL.hasOwnProperty(input)) {
        window.location.href = wordToURL[input];
    }
}
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

This example is both functional and professional looking, with essential features included. To fully utilize it, you would need to expand the `wordToURL` object with your desired word-to-URL mapping. Note that it currently navigates the same window to a new location; consider using `window.open()` if you need to open the URLs in a new tab.

Please remember to test this in a controlled environment and adapt the code to your particular needs, especially for the webpage loading feature, to ensure it's safe and secure for production use.

